@flexiarg peripherals/hot-reload-as-default-fix-path
@title Hot-Reload As Default Fix Path
@sigils [♻/續]
@audience peripheral developers, agents working inside long-running JVMs, operators
@tone operational
@style pattern
@keywords hot-reload, drawbridge, nREPL, JVM, restart, fix-cycle, blackboard, state-preservation, reconstructibility, I-0
@references [peripherals/constrained-execution-envelope peripherals/inhabitation-feeds-evolution peripherals/read-existing-seam-before-implementing realtime/single-line-transport]

! conclusion: When fixing a peripheral or any code running inside the serving JVM, hot-reload via Drawbridge nREPL is the default fix path. Restart is the exception, taken only when the change crosses a documented reload-safety boundary.

  + context: A peripheral (or anything else running inside the futon3c JVM)
    has a bug. You have a fix. You need to deploy the fix to the running
    process so observation, testing, or operator use can continue.

  + IF:
    The JVM is currently serving requests, holding session state, hosting
    other agents' work-in-progress, or simply has expensive warmth (JIT-
    compiled hot paths, loaded XTDB indexes, established WS connections).

  + HOWEVER:
    The instinct from non-JVM development is "restart and see." That
    instinct is exactly wrong here. Restarting the JVM:

    - Kills every in-flight session (operator's REPL, paired agents,
      WS subscribers, scheduled tasks)
    - Discards JIT warmth (the first N requests after restart are
      slow; this slowness propagates as backpressure cascades —
      see project_blackboard_backpressure)
    - Forces every peripheral that depends on JVM state to re-bootstrap
      (atoms reload from disk, caches re-warm, connections re-establish)
    - Triggers cascading reconnections in clients (Emacs *War Machine*
      buffers, web UIs, IRC bridges) that were not the target of the fix

    Restart is not a "clean slate" — it is an outage taken so the
    developer doesn't have to think about reload semantics.

    + FAILURE-MODES:
      - Restart-by-default: every code change becomes a JVM bounce.
        Operator and paired agents experience the bounce as cascading
        disconnects.
      - Reload-without-reading-protocol: blindly :reloading every
        changed namespace, including third-party defprotocol namespaces
        (xtdb.api, drawbridge core protocols). Reload of a protocol-
        defining ns invalidates every implementer; the cascade poisons
        the JVM and the only recovery IS a restart. (See:
        feedback_drawbridge_protocol_reload, agent memory.)
      - Reload-as-magic: assuming reload "just works" without
        understanding which namespaces are reload-safe and which are
        not. Reload safety is a property of the namespace design, not
        of the reload mechanism.
      - Hot-fix-without-disk-truth: changing something via REPL eval
        without writing the change to disk first. The fix is lost on
        the next restart and is invisible to other agents reading the
        source. Reload must always follow disk-write, never replace it.

  + THEN:
    Make hot-reload the default fix path with these disciplines:

    1. **Edit on disk first, then reload**. The disk is the source of
       truth. Reload propagates disk state into the JVM. Reloads that
       don't correspond to disk state are non-reconstructible.
    2. **Reload only your own namespaces**. Third-party namespaces
       (xtdb.api, anything that defines a protocol used by other code)
       are off-limits for reload. If you need them reloaded, restart is
       the honest answer — but it should be a deliberate decision, not
       a habit.
    3. **Reload is safe iff it equals a restart**. The test for
       reload-safety on a namespace: if you replace this namespace's
       current state with a fresh load from disk, does the JVM continue
       to behave correctly? If yes (atoms re-bootstrap from disk, no
       protocol cascade, no orphaned subscribers), the namespace is
       reload-safe. If no, restart. (See: feedback_reload_safety, agent
       memory: protocol-defining ns AND atom-without-bootstrap-replay
       are the unsafe cases.)
    4. **Use Drawbridge nREPL, not REPL eval over stdin**. Drawbridge
       provides session-scoped, observable, audit-loggable evaluation.
       proof-eval.sh and related tooling wrap it. REPL eval over stdin
       leaves no trace and bypasses the session contract.
    5. **For changes that DO require restart**, treat it as an event:
       announce it via bell, give operator and paired agents a chance
       to checkpoint, and minimize the window. A restart should feel
       like a deploy, not like a debugger gesture.

  + BECAUSE:
    Invariant I-0 (One JVM Is Plenty, futon3c CLAUDE.md) is not just
    about resource budget — it is about treating the JVM as a single,
    valuable, long-lived process whose continuity has compounding value
    over time. Every restart resets the compound interest. The JVM is
    the blackboard; the blackboard is shared infrastructure; bouncing
    shared infrastructure to deploy a one-line fix is a category error.

    The pattern also follows from the broader peripheral framing:
    peripherals generate data through inhabitation
    (inhabitation-feeds-evolution). A restart discards mid-cycle
    inhabitation data — frames in flight, half-written evidence, partial
    bell roundtrips. Hot-reload preserves the data the peripheral was
    just about to commit.

    Drawbridge is the canonical seam for this
    (peripherals/read-existing-seam-before-implementing): it exists, it
    is documented (futon3c/README-drawbridge.md), it has tooling
    (proof-eval.sh), and it is what other agents in the stack use. A
    fix path that bypasses it forks the canonical seam.

    The contrapositive is also important: hot-reload-as-default does
    NOT mean "always hot-reload, never restart." It means the choice is
    deliberate. Some changes require restart (classpath additions, JVM
    flag changes, irreversible state migrations). Recognising those
    cases and announcing the restart honestly is part of the discipline.

    + evidence: multi-watcher fix (2026-05-24, codex-8): Codex used
      proof-eval.sh to apply the multi-watcher fix to the running
      futon3c JVM without restart. The fix landed in seconds.
      Operator session, paired agents, scheduled tasks, and WS
      subscribers continued uninterrupted. The fix's verification
      happened on a JVM that was already warm.

    + evidence: feedback_no_server_restart (agent memory): "don't kill
      JVM processes; use Drawbridge nREPL for code reload." The pattern
      formalises this as the default, not just a preference.

    + evidence: feedback_drawbridge_protocol_reload (agent memory):
      "never :reload xtdb.api or any third-party defprotocol via
      Drawbridge; cascade poisons the JVM, recovery needs restart." The
      pattern names this as the boundary condition — protocol-defining
      ns is off-limits.

    + evidence: feedback_reload_safety (agent memory): "reload is safe
      iff it equals a restart." The pattern lifts this from rule into
      the test for reload-safety.

    + evidence: futon3c CLAUDE.md I-0: "For code reloads inside the
      futon3c JVM, use Drawbridge nREPL (per README-drawbridge.md); do
      not kill and restart the serving JVM." The invariant is in the
      project's CLAUDE.md; this pattern grounds the why.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - For every peripheral that runs inside the futon3c JVM, document
      which of its namespaces are reload-safe and which are not. The
      list belongs in the peripheral's own design doc.
    - When pairing on a fix, name the fix path explicitly: "hot-reload
      via Drawbridge" or "deliberate restart, here's why." Don't let
      the choice happen by reflex.
    - When designing a new peripheral, design for reload-safety from
      the start: atoms bootstrap from disk; no protocols defined in
      hot-edit paths; subscribers re-attach on reload rather than
      depending on JVM-process-identity.
    - For M-war-machine-pilot specifically: the WM peripheral's own
      namespaces should be reload-safe by design. The pilot's audit
      criteria should include "can be hot-reloaded via Drawbridge
      without disrupting the WM API surface or in-flight cycles."
